{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472399"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1355"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1355"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.76,0.02,0.11,0.08,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38671"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1355"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23064"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"717"},{"type":"tags","id":"2868"},{"type":"tags","id":"6233"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3158"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38671"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old girl presents for a routine prescription of the oral contraceptive pill. On suitability assessment, she has no contraindications to the oral contraceptive pill and before commencing the oral contraceptive pill six months ago, she had a regular 28-day cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant ongoing medical history. Last year, she had a cast for six weeks after fracturing her wrist when serving whilst playing tennis. When it happened, it was no different from any of her other serves, but she described it as extremely painful. She does not smoke or drink any alcohol and does not take any recreational drugs. She has a healthy diet consisting of red meat three times a week, regular complex carbohydrates, and vegetables.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn examination reveals all vital signs within the normal range. She has a short stature, and her BMI is 23. She has no hyperextension, tenderness, or swelling of her joints. All her cranial nerves are intact; however, she has bone conduction greater than air conduction bilaterally on Rinne\u0027s test, and her eyes are as pictured below.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Osteogenesis imperfecta","Marfan syndrome","Ehlers-Danlos syndrome","Wilson disease","Relative Energy Deficiency in Sports"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe photograph shows the characteristic blue sclera associated with the hereditary disorder, \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteogenesis imperfecta\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is associated with deficient collagen formation. There is subsequent thinning of the sclera, allowing the choroidal veins to show through, giving the blue appearance. Although this girl is asymptomatic and has only had one low impact fracture in the past, in more severe cases, patients may present with a significant number of recurrent fractures. She also has mild evidence of hearing loss and short stature on examination, which is both also consistent with osteogenesis imperfecta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMarfan\u0027s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is also a connective tissue disorder; however, it doesn\u0027t result in the blue sclera that this patient has. Furthermore, it is characterised by symptoms and signs such as a tall and slender build, chest deformities, a high arch palate, and vision changes. This patient has a short stature and hearing loss, making osteogenesis imperfecta far more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother connective tissue disorder; \u003Cstrong\u003EEhlers-Danlos syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E results in flexible joints, stretchy skin, easy fracturing due to decreased bone density, and easily bruised skin. Whilst this can be associated with blue sclera, there is nothing else in the description of this patient that would fit for Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWilson disease\u003C/strong\u003E results in an excessive copper buildup in the body. This results in a characteristic dark ring in the iris known as Kayser\u2013Fleischer rings, not blue sclera.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelative Energy Deficiency in Sports \u003C/strong\u003E(RED-S, previously known as the female athlete triad) may cause osteoporotic bones and resultant fragility fractures; however, it is also characterised by a relative metabolic energy deficit and sequelae such as fatigue, oligomenorrhoea, and a low BMI.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Blue sclera is a characteristic finding in osteogenesis imperfecta."],"references":["Tournis S, Dede AD. Osteogenesis imperfecta - A clinical update. Metabolism. 2018 Mar;80:27-37. doi: 10.1016/j.metabol.2017.06.001. Epub 2017 Jun 8. PMID: 28625337."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23064"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1355"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1741"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1741"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/28099d3f-1395-4b56-bdff-c3c428bf891e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2